<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-820-539  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 820 539.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Which Computer?andP;  Nov 1990 v13 n11 p126(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Consultancy: legal. (outsourcing) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hall, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many arrangements can be classified as facilities management; ingeneral, however, the term is used for arrangements under whichone party provides co-ordinated computer services to another.andP;  Theservice provider essentially takes on some or all of the duties ofan in-house MIS department.andP;  From the buyer's point of view,facilities management providers offer great expertise; the keydrawback to such arrangements, however, is the frightening loss ofcontrol over a core area of operations.andP;  A closely worded contractis needed.andP;  Buyers should realize that a three- to five-yearperiod, or even longer, is needed to realize the investment intime and money, and ceilings should be put on fees.andP;  Fees for allpossible services should be set forth.andP;  Fees and arrangements forbringing in new hardware and software should be covered.andP;  Thepresence of facility management staff on the buyer's premisesentails a bevy of legal problems that must be dealt with.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     OutsourcingLegal IssuesMISData SecurityContractsVendor RelationsPriceComputer ServicesFacility Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>